Robert Goldstone

2022-08-22

Project description

The JH4 intron within the immunoglobulin locus is subject to somatic hypermutation and therefore varies in sequence compared with the germline / reference.

This locus has been amplified as a 433 bp amplicon and sequenced with 2x250 bp PE reads

The goal is to align the reads with the reference sequence, quantify the number of mutations per amplicon, plot a distribution of mutational load within each sample, then compare the distribution between samples.

Tasks:

  1. Align with reference sequence
  2. Quantify number of mutations per sample
  3. Plot distribution of mutations load within each sample
  4. Compare the distribution between samples

Analysis

Well go through a couple of strategies in this report for investigating this. For all the methods, well want to merge the paired end reads from our sequencing into one read for each pair that covers the amplicon.

Step 1 - combine the reads into a consensus read.

This step involved using the commandline program bbtool. In the bbtools package, there is a function called bbmerge that overlaps reads into consensus reads

#!/usr/bin/bash

module purge
module load Miniconda3/4.7.10
conda activate bbtools

bbmerge.sh in=$read1.fastq.gz in2=$read2.fastq.gz out= merged_reads/$sample.fastq.gz

This produced a folder containing the consesnus reads for each sample

merged_reads/*

Approach 1 - using CrispRVariants

CrispRVariants is an R package that characterises variants in amplicon data. However, it seems to be best at detecting mutant clones in data referenced to a guide RNA location. It is not so easy to use it to count unique SNP variants within the population

Step 1.1 producing a reference file for CrispRVariants

The CrispRVariants R package requires a reference sequence for the region you are interested in so to call mutations. To produce this reference sequence, we use samtools faidx

module purge
module load SAMtools/1.13-GCC-10.2.0
samtools faidx $reference.fa 12:113428106-113428538 > reference.fasta

Step 1.3 using CrispRVariants to assess mutational frequency in the amplicon data

For this step, there we need to read in the reference fasta file that we made

reference <- read.fasta(file ="reference.fasta", as.string = T)
reference <- DNAString(unlist(reference))
print(reference)
## 433-letter DNAString object
## seq: CCCCACTCCACTCTTTGTCCCTATGCATCGGATACT...GCCATTCTTACCTGAGGAGACGGTGACTGAGGTTCC

With that fasta now loaded into R, we can loop through our samples and build a matrix of mutational load

my.results <- list()  # create a list to store our results in

for (i in 1:length(info_file$sample)) { # for every sample in info_file
  ref.to.use <- reference # grab the reference
  if (info_file$strand[i] == "-") { # reverse complement the reference if we need to
    ref.to.use <- reverseComplement(reference) # reverse complement the reference if we need to
  } # reverse complement the reference if we need to
  bam <- glue("{working.dir}merged_read_bam/{info_file$sample[i]}.bam") # build a file name for the bam file that belongs to this sample
  region <- GRanges(seqnames = info_file$chr[i], ranges = IRanges(info_file$start[i], info_file$end[i]), strand = info_file$strand[i]) # tell CrispRVariants what region of the genome we want to profile
  crispr_set <- readsToTarget(bam, region ,chimeras = 'exclude', reference = ref.to.use, target.loc = 0, ignore.strand = T) # run readsTotarget that does the mutation profiling
  if (is.null(crispr_set)) { # we check if it's null because some samples have no reads?
    my.results[[i]] <- NULL 
  } else { # if there is information in crispr_set (there was some reads mapping to the target)
   var_counts <- variantCounts(crispr_set, result="counts", include.nonindel = T) # count the variants
   my.results[[i]] <- var_counts # store those counts in our results
  } 
}

names(my.results) <- info_file$sample # just make the results of our loop have nice names

Next, we will just collapse the list of results into a table

my.output <- data.frame(my.results[[1]])

for (i in 2:length(my.results)) {
  my.output <- merge(my.output, my.results[[i]], by = 0, all = TRUE)
  rownames(my.output) <- my.output$Row.names
  my.output <- my.output[,-1]
}

The number of variants detected here is quite low. I think this is because CrispRVariants isnt doing exactly what we want. Firstly, rather than counting individual mutations, CrispRVariants seems to be counting mutation patterns within reads. Secondly, CrispRVariants will only count a read that completely spans the target site, meaning that mutations at the 5 or 3 extreme wont be counted.

In any case, well save these counts in case the output is useful later

write.csv(my.output, 'r_output_files/crisprvariant_variant_count.csv')

Given these limitations, well instead try to use a proper variant caller.

Approach 2 - mapping to reference and using a variant caller to define mutations

For approach 2 well use traditional variant calling mapping the reads to the mouse genome. Here, well map the reads to the mouse genome using bwa mem and then use the somatic variant caller Mutect2 to make the vcf.

2.1: mapping to genome

The consensus reads are then mapped to the mouse genome using bwa mem

#!/usr/bin/bash

module purge
module load BWA/0.7.17-foss-2018a
module load SAMtools/1.13-GCC-10.2.0

bwa mem -t 4 \
  $reference.fa \
  $sample_R1_001.fastq.gz \
  $sample_R2_001.fastq.gz |  \
  samtools view -b - | \
  samtools sort - -o bam/$sample.bam
  
samtools index $sample.bam

This resulted in the generation of several bam files that contains the mapped reads and mapping information

2.2 Calling variants with Mutect2 and producing vcf files

Mutect2 is a somatic variant caller

#!/usr/bin/bash

module purge
module load GATK/4.1.8.1-GCCcore-9.3.0-Java-1.8

gatk Mutect2 -R $reference \
  -I $sample.bam \
  -L 12:113,428,106-113,428,538 \
  -O vcf/$sample.vcf.gz

  if (length(dim(f)) > 0 ) {
    my.vcf.counts[i] <- length(f[,"CHROM"]) # the number of rows in f are the number of variants detected in the sample
    if (dim(f)[1] > 0) {
      my.melted.table <- rbind(my.melted.table, cbind(paste(f[,'CHROM'], f[,'POS'], f[,'REF'], f[,'ALT'], sep = "-"), my.samples[i], dp))
    }
  } else {
    my.vcf.counts[i] <- length(f["CHROM"])
  }
}

names(my.vcf.counts) <- my.samples
my.vcf.counts <- data.frame('sample' = names(my.vcf.counts), 'count' = my.vcf.counts)

my.cast.table <- dcast(my.melted.table,formula = V2~V1)
my.cast.table <- my.cast.table[,-1]
my.cast.table <- as.data.frame(sapply(my.cast.table, as.numeric))
rownames(my.cast.table) <- dcast(my.melted.table,formula = V2~V1)[,1]

my.cast.table <- setnafill(my.cast.table, fill = 0) # replace the NAs with 0 as it's the same thing

As the output of this process, we have a couple of datasets to explore.

the first. my.vcf.counts is a data frame of samples and the number of variants found

The second, my.cast.table is a matrix of strains vs variants with the values showing the number of reads per variant

get.counts <- function(x, vcf.object) {
  o <- data.frame('group' = character(), 'count' = numeric())
  for (i in 1:length(x)) {
    d <- as.data.frame(cbind(x[i],vcf.object[grep(paste(x[i], "", sep=""), rownames(vcf.object)),'count']))
    colnames(d) <- c('group', 'count')
    d$count <- as.numeric(d$count)
    o <- rbind(o,d)
  }
  return(o)
}

mice.data <- get.counts(mice, my.mod.vcf.counts)
tissue.data <- get.counts(tissue, my.mod.vcf.counts)
drug.data <- get.counts(drug, my.mod.vcf.counts)

ggplot(mice.data, aes(x=group, y=count)) + 
  geom_violin() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1))

ggplot(tissue.data, aes(x=group, y=count)) +

  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1))
